[Step]
Videos are stored on servers called [span className:"terms"] "data centers"[/span]: Warehouses full of giant computers designed for storing and distributing videos.
For global services, these are often placed around the world.
YouTube's parent company, Google, has 21 main data centers strategically placed throughout 4 continents (North America, South America, Europe, and Asia).
Google does not disclose the data centers they use specifically for YouTube; so all of Google's data centers are shown here.
[/Step]
[Step]
Cooling these data centers is no small feat, consuming up to 40% of the total energy required to run them.[Cite
authors:"X.Zhanga, T.Lindberg, N.Xiong, V.Vyatkinde, A.Mousavi"
title:"Cooling Energy Consumption Investigation of Data Center IT Room with Vertical Placed Server"
url:"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1876610217306331"
id:"cooling-data-center"
venue:"Energy Procedia"
date:"May 2017"
/]
Because of this, companies have begun [link text:"placing data centers in cold countries" url:"https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111904836104576560551005570810" target:"_blank"/], where they can take advantage of passive cooling.
[/Step]
[Step]
Let's take a closer look at one of these data centers. This one is in The Dalles, Oregon, on the West Coast of the United States.
[/Step]
[Step]
For information to get from this data center to you, it first goes through Google's own specialized data network to what they call "Edge Points of Presence" (POPs for short), which bring data closer to high traffic areas.
There are four metro areas with POPs in this region: Seattle, San Francisco, San Jose, and Salt Lake City.
[Button onClick:`showPops = !showPops` style:`{opacity: scrollerStages[scrollerIndex] === "pop" ? 1 : 0}`]
